- Birth defects, USA. CDC analyzed data from 15 U.S. jurisdictions conducting population-based surveillance for birth defects potentially related to Zika virus infection. All 15 U.S. jurisdictions included in this report had existing birth defects surveillance systems that were rapidly adapted to monitor birth defects potentially related to Zika virus infection. These jurisdictions provided data on live births and pregnancy losses occurring from 1 Jan - 31 Dec 2016. The prevalence of reported birth defects cases potentially related to Zika virus infection increased in jurisdictions with confirmed local transmission, from 2.8 per 1000 live births (182 cases) during the 1st half of 2016 to 3.0 per 1000 live births (211 cases) during the 2nd half (CI = 2.4-3.2 and CI = 2.6-3.4, respectively; p = 0.10). In "higher" Zika prevalence jurisdictions, the monitored birth defects prevalence was 3.0 per 1000 live births in both the 1st (753 cases) and 2nd (775 cases) halves of 2016. In "lower" prevalence jurisdictions, the monitored birth defects prevalence declined significantly from 3.4 per 1000 live births (549 cases) during the 1st half of 2016 to 3.0 (492 cases) per 1000 live births during the 2nd half (CI = 3.2-3.7 and CI = 2.8-3.3, respectively; p = 0.002).
https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/67/wr/mm6703a2.htm?s_cid=mm6703a2_w

- Preparedness USA. In a survey of 10 local health departments, 80 percent have formal and/or informal communication and referral mechanisms between their maternal and child health programs and key agency programs, such as infectious diseases and epidemiology. Also, 78 percent of respondents said they had access to electronic lab results, making it more likely for them to report to surveillance systems. More than 2/3 of them are actively engaged on response activities in their communities, such as providing information to travelers or doing clinician outreach, but are less likely to provide screening and testing services to identify potential birth defects in infants.
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2018/03/survey-finds-generally-good-local-capacity-address-zika-pregnant-women

